R Notebook

Proof-of-concept for OSM feature extraction (and preprocessing) in R.

References: (https://dominicroye.github.io/en/2018/accessing-openstreetmap-data-with-r/)

We need to ask OSM servers what features are available, so that we can filter out. The available_features() function returns a list of available OSM features that have different tags. Feature names and possible tags are kept up-to date at the OSM wiki (be prepared, is rather longish and well documented!).

In our case, we need “anything road”, so let’s ask…

# have a look at what's available
print(available_features())
 [1] "4wd_only"                "abandoned"               "abutters"               
 [4] "access"                  "addr"                    "addr:city"              
 [7] "addr:conscriptionnumber" "addr:country"            "addr:district"          
[10] "addr:flats"             
 [ reached getOption("max.print") -- omitted 205 entries ]

Whoa.

Lotsa stuff here. Reading the wiki, we can be safe asking for “highway”

# have a look at highways
available_tags("highway")
 [1] "bridleway"              "bus_guideway"           "bus_stop"              
 [4] "construction"           "corridor"               "crossing"              
 [7] "cycleway"               "elevator"               "emergency_access_point"
[10] "emergency_bay"         
 [ reached getOption("max.print") -- omitted 40 entries ]

Looks good. Looks like we need “highway” indeed. We also have to define some spatial boundaries, since we just want to deal with – say – a slice of Northern Italy. Fix that bounding box issue, theh back to tamper with OSM.

:question: :construction: Note that in osmdata one explicits bounding boxes by place names, whereas real mapmakers use real bounding boxes. So much for the Muggles. Well’fix that later.

# we have an AOI polygon in BASE, I used the boundaries of Piedmont and Lombardy, plus a 10 km buffer, then reprojected from 23032 into 4326.

# tis is the standard osmdata mechanism, what if we have an extent?
bb <- getbb("Piemonte")
background.map <- get_map(bb, maptype = "toner-background")
maptype = "toner-background" is only available with source = "stamen".
resetting to source = "stamen"...
ggmap(background.map)

So far, so good, we can (albeit in a silly way) hook up a part of the world. Back to highway, now.

# note the use of tidyverse piping
# note 2 set a timeout value high enough to opq
q <- getbb("Piemonte") %>% opq(timeout=900) %>% add_osm_feature("highway")
roads <- osmdata_sf(q) # this takes ages

# well, try a plot
ggmap(background.map) + geom_sf(data=roads$osm_points,
                                inherit.aes = FALSE,
          colour = "#238443",
          fill = "#004529",
          alpha = .5,
          size = 4,
          shape = 21)+
  labs(x = "", y = "")
